By STANLEY NWANOSIKE ENUGU- An activist, Mr Olu Omotayo, has urged politicians and public office holders to learn some lessons from Chief Justice of Nigeria (CJN), Justice  Muhammad Tanko’s resignation and know the right time to quit.The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) recalls that Justice Tanko resigned as the CJN on Monday, June 27, due to ill health.Omotayo, who is the President of Civil Rights Realisation and Advancement Network (CRRAN), made the call while speaking with NAN in Enugu on Wednesday.He noted that “it is a good development and truly the first time in history in Africa”.The activist said he acted in the overall benefit of the Nigeria’s judiciary and the nation at large since he could not continue.“It is rare in this part of the world to see someone resign honourably and voluntarily from an exalted position. “CJN Justice Tanko clearly knew that his ill-health was interfering in his job and he may not easily cope going forward,” he said.Omotayo urged Nigerians to put safety and health first before any other material or position considerations. (NAN) By ISMAILA CHAFE ABUJA- President Muhammadu Buhari on Monday swore in Justice Olukayode Ariwoola as the acting Chief Justice of Nigeria (CJN).The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that the swearing of Ariwoola, the next most senior in the hierarchy of the Supreme Court, as the new CJN followed the… In "News" By ISMAILA CHAFE The President, Major General Muhammadu Buhari (retd.), shakes hand with acting CJN Olukayode Ariwoola ABUJA- President Muhammadu Buhari says he is constrained to accept the resignation of the Chief Justice of Nigeria (CJN), Justice Muhammad Tanko on health groundsThe president stated this while swearing in Justice Olukayode… In "News" Justice Tanko Muhammad ABUJA - Justice Ibrahim Tanko Muhammad has resigned as the Chief Justice of Nigeria (CJN). He reportedly tendered his resignation in a letter to President Muhammadu... Justice Ibrahim Tanko Muhammad has resigned as the Chief Justice 